<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cortaderia </i>species are large tussock grasses with big showy plumes with abundant small seeds. They produce seeds sexually or asexually; all seeds are highly fertile, small, and easily dispersed by wind, water, and machinery. Plants have broad habitat requirements and grow vigorously. Growing best in full sunshine with adequate water, plants can tolerate drought conditions once they are established. Plants produce a large amount of dry matter that easily burns (DiTomaso 2000a,b, DiTomaso and Healy 2007, Peterson and Russo 1988). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Cortaderia jubata, </i>jubata grass, has a Cal-IPC rank of High. Plants flourish in foggy coastal habitats that are generally free of freezing temperatures. Several consecutive nights of frost will generally not kill plants but can severely damage them. The species reproduces asexually. Plants were first found in the state on recently logged lands of Humboldt Co. (Fuller 1976). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Cortaderia selloana, </i>pampas grass, has a Cal-IPC rank of High. It reproduces sexually by seed when both male and female plants are present, and it escapes from cultivation by fragmentation. <i>C. selloana </i>is a more invasive species and invades a greater variety of vegetation types from coastal to inland California than does <i>C. jubata </i>(Lambrinos 2001); <i>C. selloana </i>tolerates more frost and more-continental climates (DiTomaso 2000b). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Cortaderia </i>invade coastal bluff and coastal scrub stands of <i>Artemisia californica, Baccharis pilularis, </i>and <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>alliances. They grow in moist, open forest stands and infest inland riparian stands in the Great Valley. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
