    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). Stands of both species occur along the coast on steep slopes, bluffs, and road cuts. Stands are common in the San Francisco Bay Area, particularly at the disturbed edges of salt marshes (e.g., Oakland Airport). State parks have managed stands to eliminate their spread, including patches of <i>C. jubata </i>at Morro Strand State Beach (Walgren et al. 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-b, Af). Cortaderia has been seen along Alameda Creek near Sunol and near tributaries above San Juan Canyon near San Juan Bautista (CalFlora 2019).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Af-g, Al). Small stands of <i>C. selloana </i>observed on moist soils in association with <i>Juncus arcticus </i>or <I>J</i>. <i>lescurii </i>occur along levees and in disturbed portions of Suisun Marsh (Vaghti and Keeler-Wolf 2000) and the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Stands at Suisun Marsh did increase during 4 years of monitoring (Vaghti and Keeler-Wolf 2004). Though mostly existing scattered individuals, and under active management, at least one small stand exists along the lower American River (Maret, pers. Communication 2019), and <i>C. selloana</i> has infestations under management on the Feather River around Thermolito (CalFlora 2019, CalIPC 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). <i>Cortaderia jubata </i>commonly invades logged forest sites. It dies out as tree canopies develop and reduce light levels. However, it persists in stands of coastal dune and scrub alliances. Monitoring and manual removal has kept the Lanphere Dunes unit of the Humboldt Bay National Refuge and other conservation areas on the north spit of Humboldt Bay in Humboldt Co. free of <i>C. jubata</i>.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb, Bd-f). Infestations of <i>Cortaderia</i> are known to be increasing around Clear Lake and Lake Berryessa (Cal-IPC 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands of both grasses invade maritime chaparral and coastal scrub
alliances along the coast, including at Vandenberg Air Force Base and near Lompoc and Santa Maria in Santa Barbara Co. (Lambrinos 2000, 2002, Underwood et al. 2002), south to San Diego Co. (DiTomaso et al. 1999).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g). Stands of <i>C. selloana </i>exist in the western Transverse Ranges.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cortaderia </i>species invade and threaten California’s native coastal vegetation types, particularly those in sensitive coastal dune and bluff scrub areas. In logged redwood forests of northern California, <i>C. jubata </i>can retard tree establishment and growth, and it can create fire hazards by accumulating biomass of living and dried vegetation and by impeding access to areas (DiTomaso et al. 1999). Prescribed burning does not furnish long-term control, as burned plants sprout. See DiTomaso (2000a, 2001b) and DiTomoso and Healy (2007) for a review of manual and chemical control measures. </div>
</div>

    

    

